    en: "New York's Fair Chance Act bars most employers from asking about criminal history on a job application or during an interview before making a conditional offer of employment. Once a conditional offer is on the table, the employer can run a background check. If the employer wants to withdraw the offer based on a conviction, Correction Law Article 23-A requires the employer to run a specific case-by-case analysis, share it in writing with the applicant, and give the applicant time to respond. Blanket no-conviction hiring policies are illegal. The Fair Chance Act applies to all New York employers regardless of size (the four-employee minimum was removed effective Feb 8, 2020). NYC has its own stricter Fair Chance Act on top."
